,"9 July 1471":"9. července 1471","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, Anglie"},"da":{"9 July 1471–1502":"9. juli 1471–1502","1471–1502":"1471–1502","1468–1523":"1468–1523","1502–1547":"1502–1547","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1547":"1547","before 1502":"før 1502","1502":"1502","1523":"1523","1468":"1468","1453":"1453","1451":"1451","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","9 July 1471":"9. juli 1471","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England"},"nl":{"9 July 1471–1502":"9 juli 1471–1502","1471–1502":"1471–1502","1468–1523":"1468–1523","1502–1547":"1502–1547","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1547":"1547","before 1502":"vóór 1502","1502":"1502","1523":"1523","1468":"1468","1453":"1453","1451":"1451","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","9 July 1471":"9 juli 1471","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"9 July 1471–1502":"9 July 1471–1502","1471–1502":"1471–1502","1468–1523":"1468–1523","1502–1547":"1502–1547","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1547":"1547","before 1502":"before 1502","1502":"1502","1523":"1523","1468":"1468","1453":"1453","1451":"1451","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","9 July 1471":"9 July 1471","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clark","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>clerk</i>, <i>clark</i> ‘clerk, cleric, writer’ (Old French <i>clerc</i>; see   Clerc  ). The original sense was ‘man in a religious order, cleric, clergyman’. As all writing and secretarial work in medieval Christian Europe was normally done by members of the clergy, the term <i>clerk</i> came to mean ‘scholar, secretary, recorder, or penman’ as well as ‘cleric’. As a surname, it was particularly common for one who had taken only minor holy orders. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established.","Irish (Westmeath, Mayo): in Ireland the English surname was frequently adopted, partly by translation for <i>Ó Cléirigh</i>; see   Cleary  .","Americanized form of Dutch   De Klerk   or Flemish   De Clerck   or of variants of these names, and possibly also of French   Clerc  . Compare   Clerk   2 and   De Clark  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Clarke","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Clark  .","History: This name was brought independently to New England by many bearers from the 17th century onward. Nicholas Clarke was one of the founders of Hartford, CT (coming from Cambridge, MA with Thomas Hooker) in 1635."]},{"name":"Clerk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Pierre, Jacques.","English: variant of   Clark  .","Americanized form of French   Clerc   and perhaps also of the Dutch and Flemish cognates   De Klerk   and   De Clerck   or of variants of these names. Compare   Clark   3."]},{"name":"Clerkin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Liam, Brendan, Dympna, Seamus.","Irish (Monaghan): from an Irish pet form of English <i>clerk</i> ‘cleric’ (Irish <i>cléireach</i>), see   Clark  . Alternatively, an Anglicized form of <b>Ó Cléireacháin</b>, ‘descendant of little cleric’, an Irish diminutive of the word. See also   McClurkin  , an Antrim surname from <i>Mac Cléirchín</i> ‘son of little cleric’."]},{"name":"Calarco","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Rocco, Angelo, Carmelo, Fausto, Nunziato, Salvatore.","Italian (southern): probably a nickname derived from Greek <i>kalē archē</i> ‘good beginning’. Compare   Clark   4."]},{"name":"Clerc","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Alain, Odette, Sebastien, Serge.","French: occupational or status name for a member of a minor religious order or for a scholar, Old French <i>clerc</i>, from Late Latin <i>clericus</i>, from Greek <i>klērikos</i>, a derivative of <i>klēros</i> ‘inheritance, legacy’, with reference to the priestly tribe of Levites (see   Levy  ) ‘whose inheritance was the Lord’. In medieval Christian Europe, clergy in minor orders were permitted to marry and so found families; thus the surname could become established. In the Middle Ages it was virtually only members of religious orders who learned to read and write, so that the term <i>clerc</i> later came to denote any literate man, a scholar (hence its modern meaning ‘scribe, secretary’ or ‘clerk’). Compare   Leclerc  ."]},{"name":"Clarkson","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): patronymic from   Clark  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Màiri ."],"variants":[{"name":"Màiri","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Mary</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Mary Elizabeth Clark was born on 9 July 1471, in Syleham, Suffolk, England, her father, Edward Watson Clark, was 20 and her mother, Sarah Jane Decker, was 18. She married William John Middleton before 1502. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1502, in her hometown, at the age of 31."},"et":{"9 July 1471–1502":"9. juuli 1471–1502","1471–1502":"1471–1502","1468–1523":"1468–1523","1502–1547":"1502–1547","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1547":"1547","before 1502":"enne 1502","1502":"1502","1523":"1523","1468":"1468","1453":"1453","1451":"1451","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","9 July 1471":"9. juuli 1471","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"9 July 1471–1502":"9. heinäkuuta 1471–1502","1471–1502":"1471–1502","1468–1523":"1468–1523","1502–1547":"1502–1547","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1547":"1547","before 1502":"ennen vuotta 1502","1502":"1502","1523":"1523","1468":"1468","1453":"1453","1451":"1451","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","9 July 1471":"9. heinäkuuta 1471","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"9 July 1471–1502":"9 juillet 1471–1502","1471–1502":"1471–1502","1468–1523":"1468–1523","1502–1547":"1502–1547","1451–1470":"1451–1470","1453–1470":"1453–1470","1547":"1547","before 1502":"avant 1502","1502":"1502","1523":"1523","1468":"1468","1453":"1453","1451":"1451","1471":"1471","1470":"1470","9 July 1471":"9 juillet 1471","Syleham, Suffolk, England":"Syleham, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lady Mary Elizabeth Clark est née le 9 juillet 1471, à Syleham, Suffolk, Angleterre, son père, Edward Watson Clark, avait 20 ans et sa mère, Sarah Jane Decker, avait 18 ans. Elle a épousé William John Middleton avant 1502. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Elle est décédée en 1502, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 31 ans."},"de":{"9 July 1471–1502":"9. Juli 1471–1502","1471–1502":"1471–1502","1468–1523":"1468–1523","1502–1547"